<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-158-696  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 158 696.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  Feb 12 1990 v218 n7 p48(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Bell of Pennsylvania is optically driven. (optically driven remoteswitching units, includes a related article on the city ofPittsburgh)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Furey, Harvey R.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Bell of Pennsylvania has begun using optically driven remoteswitching units (RSU) as an economical way of expanding andenhancing service in dense areas around Pittsburgh.andP;  The companyfound it could save $225,000 by installing an RSU compared to thecost of installing a digital loop carrier (DLC) systems.andP;  DLCsprove to be cheaper for applications with less than 1,000 lines,but for between 1,000 and 2,000 lines RSUs have the advantage.andO;Optically driven RSUs communicate directly with the processor atthe host switch using two pairs of single-mode optical fiber,making a switching module unnecessary.andP;  The two pairs of opticalfiber can handle all the traffic for a fully loaded RSU, withoutthe need to engineer and provision the normal T-1 links.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Bell Telephone Company of Pennsylvania (services).andO;Topic:     Fiber opticsSwitching CentersTelephone Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>